text.tspan: (3) Topics in the document collection and their word distributions
(2) The topic distribution of a document

flowRoot.flowPara: A central problem of meta-scientific research is the need to summarise the contents of large collections of documents an infeasible task for humans to perform unassisted. Topic models are big-data algorithms for discovering the main themes (or 'topics') that pervade a large and otherwise unstructured collection of documents. They proceed on the assumption that words systematically co-occur within documents, and that repeated co-occurances indicate a shared semantic structure across the collection (Blei 2012).

In this illustrative example (not fitted to real data), the well-known paper by Kates et al. (2001) is bundled within a larger collection of documents on sustainability science (1). Each document is comprised of multiple topics (2), based on its contents (highlighted), and the systematic co-occurence of words across the collection (3). Thus "sustainable development", "nature and society", and "scientific research" appear to be prevalent topics in this paper. A fourth topic, apparently on climate change, is not prominent in this paper, but can be found in the wider document collection.
